</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="16F2EEAABF58FFE1FF66F8CFFEC0FEBC" lastPageId="20" lastPageNumber="21" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="description">
<paragraph id="5E57BD21BF58FFE1FF66F8CFFEC0FEBC" blockId="19.[151,1436,1758,2035]" lastBlockId="20.[151,1437,151,644]" lastPageId="20" lastPageNumber="21" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis id="6C9C6133BF58FFE6FF66F8CFFEA9F8C3" bold="true" box="[199,337,1794,1819]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Description</emphasis>
. Stems up to 
<quantity id="991010C4BF58FFE6FE56F8CFFDC3F8C2" box="[503,571,1794,1818]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="mm" value="5.0">5 mm</quantity>
high arising from creeping, branching hydrorhiza. Basal part above origin from stolon short, either smooth or wrinkled. Remainder of stem divided into internodes by means of transverse to slightly oblique nodes, 
<number id="E820AF06BF58FFE6FE01F887FE1DF8BA" box="[416,485,1866,1890]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" value="67.5" valueMax="70.0" valueMin="65.0">65–70</number>
µm wide; perisarc thin and smooth. Each internode 
<number id="E820AF06BF58FFE6FB9AF887FB65F8BA" box="[1083,1181,1866,1890]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" value="617.5" valueMax="690.0" valueMin="545.0">545–690</number>
µm long, with a basal bulge above the proximal node, a terminal hydrotheca, and a latero-distal apophysis supporting the following internode. Branching occasional, with side branches given off laterally through a second distal stem apophysis, the hydrotheca thus becoming axillar; branches short, generally composed of a single hydranthopore. Hydrotheca shallow, 
<emphasis id="6C9C6133BF58FFE6FF58F811FEECF82B" box="[249,276,2012,2035]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">ca</emphasis>
. 
<number id="E820AF06BF58FFE6FE80F817FEC5F82A" box="[289,317,2010,2034]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" value="25.0">25</number>
µm deep, 
<number id="E820AF06BF58FFE6FE13F817FDECF82A" box="[434,532,2010,2034]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" value="125.0" valueMax="130.0" valueMin="120.0">120–130</number>
µm wide at diaphragm and 
<number id="E820AF06BF58FFE6FCEAF817FC55F82A" box="[843,941,2010,2034]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" value="142.5" valueMax="150.0" valueMin="135.0">135–150</number>
µm at aperture; walls somewhat flaring, rim not everted; a row of desmocytes above the diaphragm; renovations not seen. Hydranths with 
<number id="E820AF06BF5FFFE1FB42FF5AFAD0FF77" box="[1251,1320,151,175]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="20.0" valueMax="21.0" valueMin="19.0">19–21</number>
tentacles. Gonothecae, male in the present material, club shaped, 
<number id="E820AF06BF5FFFE1FCB8FF71FC83FF0C" box="[793,891,188,212]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="700.0" valueMax="790.0" valueMin="610.0">610–790</number>
µm long, 
<number id="E820AF06BF5FFFE1FC56FF71FBA0FF0C" box="[1015,1112,188,212]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="217.5" valueMax="250.0" valueMin="185.0">185–250</number>
µm wide, tapering abruptly proximally into indistinct pedicel, rounded distally. Cnidome: 
<number id="E820AF06BF5FFFE1FCCCFF12FC81FF2F" box="[877,889,223,247]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="1.0">1</number>
) microbasic mastigophores, (
<number id="E820AF06BF5FFFE1FB72FF12FAD3FF2F" box="[1235,1323,223,247]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="6.5" valueMax="6.6" valueMin="6.4">6.4–6.6</number>
)× 
<number id="E820AF06BF5FFFE1FAE3FF12FA9CFF2F" box="[1346,1380,223,247]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="1.9">1.9</number>
µm, abundant in the tentacles, also scattered in the coenosarc; 
<number id="E820AF06BF5FFFE1FCE9FEC9FCAFFEC4" box="[840,855,260,284]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="2.0">2</number>
) microbasic heteronemes, slightly wider than the mastigophores, 
<emphasis id="6C9C6133BF5FFFE1FEE8FEE4FE9CFE98" box="[329,356,297,320]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">ca</emphasis>
. 
<number id="E820AF06BF5FFFE1FED3FEEAFE6DFEE7" box="[370,405,295,319]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="6.6">6.6</number>
× 
<number id="E820AF06BF5FFFE1FE05FEEAFE30FEE7" box="[420,456,295,319]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="2.4">2.4</number>
µm, rare in the coenosarc; 
<number id="E820AF06BF5FFFE1FD5CFEEAFCF3FEE7" box="[765,779,295,319]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="3.0">3</number>
) pseudostenoteles, (
<number id="E820AF06BF5FFFE1FC51FEEAFB9BFEE7" box="[1008,1123,295,319]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="10.95" valueMax="11.6" valueMin="10.3">10.3–11.6</number>
)×(
<number id="E820AF06BF5FFFE1FB23FEEAFB20FEE7" box="[1154,1240,295,319]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="5.449999999999999" valueMax="6.1" valueMin="4.8">4.8–6.1</number>
) µm, common in the coenosarc.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="16F2EEAABF5FFFE1FF66FEBDFCA7FD5C" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="5E57BD21BF5FFFE1FF66FEBDFE45FD87" blockId="20.[151,1437,151,644]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis id="6C9C6133BF5FFFE1FF66FEBDFECCFE50" bold="true" box="[199,308,368,392]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Remarks</emphasis>
. This specimen comes close to 
<taxonomicName id="99E8C6A2BF5FFFE1FD34FEBCFC32FE5F" authority="Calder, 1991" authorityName="Calder" authorityYear="1991" box="[661,970,367,392]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Haleciidae" genus="Halecium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="lightbourni">
<emphasis id="6C9C6133BF5FFFE1FD34FEBCFCCDFE50" box="[661,821,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">H. lightbourni</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="3A79C0D0BF5FFFE1FC9AFEA2FC32FE5F" author="Calder" box="[827,970,367,391]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" refString="Calder, D. R. (1991) Shallow-water hydroids of Bermuda: the Thecatae, exclusive of Plumularioidea. Royal Ontario Museum Life Sciences Contributions, 154, 1 - 140. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.2307 / 1352274" type="journal article" year="1991">
Calder, 
<number id="E820AF06BF5FFFE1FC33FEA2FC32FE5F" box="[914,970,367,391]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="1991.0">1991</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
with respect to the shape and size of both internodes and hydrotheca. However, a difference in the cnidome composition prevents identification as this species: the small microbasic eurytele illustrated by Calder in his Fig. 
<number id="E820AF06BF5FFFE1FC75FE7AFC15FE17" box="[980,1005,439,463]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="11.0">11</number>
A looks distinct from the microbasic heteronemes occurring in this material. In addition, I think that what Calder identified as large microbasic euryteles are instead pseudostenoteles. Indeed, the same capsules occur in specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="99E8C6A2BF5FFFE1FB9EFDCCFA64FDCF" authority="Allman, 1888" authorityName="Allman" authorityYear="1888" box="[1087,1436,511,536]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Haleciidae" genus="Halecium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="dichotomum">
<emphasis id="6C9C6133BF5FFFE1FB9EFDCCFB08FDC0" box="[1087,1264,512,536]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">H. dichotomum</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="3A79C0D0BF5FFFE1FB5DFE32FA64FDCF" author="Allman" box="[1276,1436,511,535]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" refString="Allman, G. J. (1888) Report on the Hydroida dredged by H. M. S. Challenger during the years 1873 - 76. Part II. - The Tubularinae, Corymorphinae, Campanularinae, Sertularinae and Thalamophora. Report on the Scientific Results of the Voyage of H. M. S. Challenger during the year 1873 - 76, Zoology, 23 (70), 1 - 90." type="journal article" year="1888">
Allman, 
<number id="E820AF06BF5FFFE1FAC5FE32FA64FDCF" box="[1380,1436,511,535]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="1888.0">1888</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
examined here and, though no discharged nematocysts could be found, I follow 
<bibRefCitation id="3A79C0D0BF5FFFE1FBB4FDE9FB3AFDE4" author="Migotto" box="[1045,1218,548,572]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" refString="Migotto, A. E. (1996) Benthic shallow-water hydroids (Cnidaria, Hydrozoa) of the coast of Sao Sebastiao, Brazil, including a checklist of Brazilian hydroids. Zoologische Verhandelingen, Leiden, 306, 1 - 125." type="journal article" year="1996">
Migotto (
<number id="E820AF06BF5FFFE1FBDFFDE9FB42FDE4" box="[1150,1210,548,572]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="1996.0">1996</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, who indicated that they are pseudostenoteles.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5E57BD21BF5FFFE1FF66FDA6FCA7FD5C" blockId="20.[151,1437,151,644]" box="[199,863,619,644]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis id="6C9C6133BF5FFFE1FF66FDA6FE05FD5C" bold="true" box="[199,509,619,644]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Geographical distribution</emphasis>
. Only known from 
<collectingCountry id="26FFFDB1BF5FFFE1FD7AFDA1FCA3FD5C" box="[731,859,620,644]" name="Martinique" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Martinique</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
